[1] USA: California (San Diego County)
[2] USA: California (Kearn County)

******
[1] USA: California (San Diego County)
Date: Mon 24 Mar 2008
Source: KPBS [edited]
<http://www.kpbs.org/news/local;id=11226>


More dead birds infected with West Nile virus have been found in San
Diego County. It's the earliest time of the year the disease has ever
been detected here.

In January [2008], a red-tailed hawk was found in Escondido with West
Nile virus. Since then, the disease has been detected in at least 5
other birds in various parts of the County.

Chris Conlan with the San Diego County's vector control division says
he can't really account for the early appearance of West Nile [virus
transmission] this year [2008]. He adds, "West Nile [virus] hasn't
been here all that long; it's still a relatively new disease. And
this just could be a sign of what happens after it's gotten
established in an area for a while. But honestly, I don't really know."

Last year [2007] in San Diego County, 15 people became infected with
West Nile virus. Statewide in 2007, the disease sickened 380 people,
and killed 20.

[Byline: Kenny Goldberg]

